to correct the damage. If the damage is not corrected or if the cell cannot put the DNA back together in its original form, then mutations result which can lead to cancer or inherited disease. ||Cells have evolved sets of proteins, termed repair enzymes, to tackle the damage, but in some individuals these enzymes are lacking or do not function properly. The study of these enzymes and the people who lack them is of great importance in understanding, and ultimately influencing, the onset of cancer and inherited disease.||</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>Summary of aims: To map and clone human DNA repair genes involved in sensitivity to DNA damaging agents, especially ionizing radiation; To assess the molecular and cellular functions of cloned repair genes involved in homologous recombination and related processes, and to relate these genes to human sensitivity disorders;||DNA repair processes occupy a central cellular role as the major defence against damage incurred by environmental agents (radiation, chemicals) and from metabolic processes (e.g., oxidative by-products). Several human disorders are known or suspected to have DNA repair defects; these are hypersensitive to environmental agents and generally show cancer-proneness. While these disorders tend to be rare, it is suspected that carriers of defective repair genes (who will probably form several percent of the population) show some of the phenotypic effects of fully defective individuals. The isolation and characterization of the genes and proteins involved in these processes is of considerable importance to provide tools to identify those at risk, and to moderate medical procedures such as radiotherapy. The study of the mechanisms of mutation formation identifies the processes contributing to both genetic disorders and cancer.||Current work embraces studies of gene function using molecular, cellular and animal methodology. Functions are assessed by a battery of methods: protein expression, purification and antibody production; protein:protein interactions by 2-hybrid analysis; quantitative PCR analysis of transcript expression; creation of knockouts in mice and lower organisms; measurement of molecular recombination and effects on chromosomal segregation; etc. ||</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2007-03-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>1976-04-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>EXPENDITURE_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>651988</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">MC_U142736331</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories><gtr:healthCategory><gtr:id>7C58A707-1BF6-4573-A44F-30B271C80813</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>100</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Cancer</gtr:text></gtr:healthCategory></gtr:healthCategories><gtr:researchActivities><gtr:researchActivity><gtr:id>CDB856E6-DF2D-4D96-88BD-1CC96FE277EF</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>100</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>2.2  Factors relating to physical environment</gtr:text></gtr:researchActivity></gtr:researchActivities><gtr:researchSubjects/><gtr:researchTopics/><gtr:rcukProgrammes/></gtr:project></gtr:projectComposition></gtr:projectOverview>